&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Buoyant Force&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Buoyant force is the upward force exerted by a fluid that opposes the weight of an object immersed in it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This force arises because the fluid displaced by the object creates a pressure difference between the top and bottom of the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Buoyant force is governed by Archimedes&amp;#39; principle, which states that the upward force is equal to the weight of the fluid displaced.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It plays a crucial role in enabling objects like ships to float on water and balloons to rise in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Buoyant force depends on the density of the fluid and the volume of the object submerged.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Archimedes&amp;#39; Principle:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Discovered by the Greek mathematician Archimedes, this principle explains buoyancy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It states that a body submerged in a fluid experiences an upward force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Density and Buoyancy:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An object floats if its density is less than the density of the fluid it is immersed in.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Objects denser than the fluid sink due to insufficient buoyant force to counter their weight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Buoyant Force:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in designing ships, submarines, and floating devices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps in understanding the functioning of hot air balloons and hydrometers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Factors Affecting Buoyant Force:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The volume of the object submerged: Larger volume displaces more fluid, increasing buoyant force.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The density of the fluid: Higher density fluids exert greater buoyant force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;683&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The luminous efficacy of monochromatic radiation at a frequency of &lt;strong&gt;540 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;12&lt;/sup&gt; Hz&lt;/strong&gt; corresponds to the wavelength of approximately 555 nm in the visible spectrum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The value of luminous efficacy for this specific wavelength is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;maximum possible luminous efficacy&lt;/strong&gt; for any monochromatic light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;standard value of luminous efficacy&lt;/strong&gt; for monochromatic light at 555 nm is &lt;strong&gt;683 lumen per watt&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This value is used as the reference point for the photopic vision curve, which represents the sensitivity of the human eye to various wavelengths of light under well-lit conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The unit lumen per watt (lm/W) is a measure of how efficiently a light source converts energy into visible light perceived by the human eye.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Luminous Efficacy:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Luminous efficacy is a measure of how well a light source produces visible light.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is expressed in lumens per watt (lm/W) and considers the human eye&amp;#39;s response to different wavelengths.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Photopic Vision:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Photopic vision refers to the eye&amp;#39;s sensitivity to light under well-lit conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The peak sensitivity occurs at a wavelength of 555 nm, corresponding to green light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wavelength and Frequency Relationship:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The wavelength (&amp;lambda;) and frequency (f) of light are related by the equation c = &amp;lambda; &amp;times; f, where c is the speed of light (approximately 3 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt; m/s).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For a frequency of 540 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;12&lt;/sup&gt; Hz, the wavelength is approximately 555 nm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Luminous Efficacy:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a critical parameter for evaluating the energy efficiency of lighting systems such as LEDs, incandescent bulbs, and fluorescent lamps.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Higher luminous efficacy indicates more efficient light generation with less energy consumption.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

